10.body:
A database file (or file or table store ) is a series of pages . Note This file is an actual file on the disk. The file should support: iterating over the pages performing read, cread, update, delete on the pages. Example Files are typically stores in /var/lib/postgresql/data. In Postgres, we can see it via SHOW data_directory; Table data is stored in the base folder. To know which folder is for which database: SELECT oid, datname
FROM pg_database; To know which folder is for which table(s), you can do SELECT oid, relname, relkind
FROM pg_class
WHERE relkind IN ('r', 'i'); The job of a disk space manager is: to manage the database files to keep track of what data has been read and written to pages to keep track of how much free space there is in the pages There are different ways to do this. File organisation looks into this. Postgres In Postgres, a table or index is stored in one or more files. When a table or index grows more than 1GB, Postgres uses additional files. SQLite SQLite uses 1 file for the entire database. interface PageManagement { val pages: HashMap<PageId, Page> val freeSpaces: HashMap<PageId, Int> val records: HashMap<PageId, List<RecordId>>
}
10.title: File

12.body: A database page (or simply a page ) is a fixed-size block of data consisting of records, indexes etc. (most systems will not mix the different types together within a page). Postgres In Postgres, the page size is 8KB. See this for yourself in /var/lib/postgresql/data/base. A page is the unit of (i) storage allocation and (ii) data transfer.
12.title: Page

13.body:
Postgres Postgres uses the slotted page structure for its table and index pages. Below is an example of slotted page Page 7 with 3 slots corresponding to 3 different records. Page 7 0 4 8 12 ... 28
<start of page> +----------------------------------------------------+ | <somerecordA> <somerecordB> | +----------------------------------------------------+ | <somerecordC> | +----------------------------------------------------+ | * | +----------------------------------------------------+ | | +----------------------------------------------------+ | | <28,16> | <04,20> | <64,28> | 03 | 92 | 4096 | +----------------------------------------------------+ <end of page> ^ ^ ^ | | | slot slot slot The numbers tell a story, if we read them backward from the end of the page: 4096 - the total page size in bytes 92 - offset to start writing into the free space, which starts from * 3 - total number of slots <64,28> - the location of a record located 64 bytes from the start of the page. This record is 28 bytes long. <04,20> - the location of a record located 04 bytes from the start of the page. This record is 20 bytes long. <28,16> - the location of a record located 28 bytes from the start of the page. This record is 16 bytes long. The three different records and their corresponding record IDs and slots: Record Record ID Slot somerecordA (7,1) <04,20> somerecordB (7,2) <28,16> somerecordC (7,0) <64,28> In a slotted page, there are 2 directions where data is written: Records are written downwards (from start to end of page) Slots are written upwards (from end to start of page)

14.body:
A record or tuple is a database row in a row-oriented column. Every record is associated with a record ID . A record ID is typically (page_id, slot_number). A record can have 2 different formats: Fixed length +----+----------+------+
| | | |
+----+----------+------+ Here you have 3 columns of fixed types. Variable length Array of fields delimited by special symbols Array of field offsets Postgres Postgres uses a variable-length record format. Additionally it uses TOAST for large data values that don't fit a page.

16.body: A frame is a unit of memory, typically the same as page size A buffer pool is a collection of frames in memory.

17.body: The buffer manager manages page requests. For every frame in the buffer pool, it needs to keep track of the frame's page ID pin count - a counter dirty flag - if the frame's page has been modified The buffer pool has a limited number of frames available. Eviction policy or buffer replacement policy chooses a frame for replacement when the buffer pool needs to free up a frame. Some policies are: LRU (Least Recently Used) MRU (Most Recently Used) Clock Flush buffer In Postgres, to flush a buffer, do: CHECKPOINT

20.body: The DBMS ensures that the contents of the table and the index are logically in sync. Note that primary keys are always indexed. Indexes are used for: point lookup range lookup prefix search geo-location lookup Two types of indices: Ordered indices - B+ tree (common) Hash indices - Hash table

23.body: A query execution plan is represented as a tree (" plan tree "). The tree consists of nodes, where each node represents an operation. See the execution plan In Postgres, you can view the plan for a given query: EXPLAIN SELECT * FROM some_table; To run the query and retrieve statistics: EXPLAIN ANALYZE SELECT * FROM some_table;

3.body: Transactional statements : SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE, and ALTER TABLE. These can be grouped within a BEGIN ... COMMIT block, or they can each be automatically committed if executed outside of an explicit transaction. Non-transactional statements : Some SQL commands cannot be rolled back once executed, even if they are inside a transaction. Eg. CREATE DATABASE or DROP DATABASE Autocommit behavior : By default, PostgreSQL uses autocommit mode, meaning that every individual statement is wrapped in its own transaction and automatically committed unless you explicitly start a transaction block. Warning Note that client libraries or frameworks might automatically rollback a transaction when an error occurs. BEGIN; -- operations... COMMIT;
3.title: Transaction

30.body: A cost model is an estimation of the cost of executing a plan. DBMS use this. The cost of the query depends on: CPU Disk I/O - the no. of block transfers Memory - the amount of DRAM used Network
30.title: Cost model

31.body: A process model defines how the system supports concurrent requests. The DBMS is comprised of one or more workers . Each worker is responsible for executing tasks on behalf of the client and returning the results. Process models: Process per worker Process pool Thread per worker Database Process per worker Process pool Thread per worker Postgres y Oracle y IBM DB2 y SQLite SQL Server MySQL Query parallelism: Inter-query parallelism Intra-query parallelism Intra-Operator Parallelism (Horizontal) Inter-Operator Parallelism (Vertical) Bushy Parallelism I/O parallelism: Multi-Disk Parallelism Database Partitioning
31.title: Parallel execution

32.body: A transaction is the execution of a sequence of one or more operations.
32.title: Transaction

34.body: To prevent concurrent writes , databases often provide mechanisms to lock rows or tables. When a process locks a row/table, other processes must wait until the lock is released before they can make their own changes. This ensures that updates are applied in a certain order. Warning Locking may introduce performance bottlenecks.
34.title: Locking

35.body: Write-ahead log Data is typically written to a write-ahead log before being indexed in a B-tree. Postgres In Postgres, every change ot the database is first written to the WAL. The actual database files are updated later, based on the WAL. SQLite In SQLite, the reader (processes querying the database) access data from both the main database file and the WAL files. See WAL in Postgres Go to the directory $ cd $PGDATA/waldump View the log file $ ls Dump $ pg_waldump <log-file>
35.title: WAL

36.body: Records all transactions and updates to the database.
36.title: Transaction log

37.title: Replication log

38.body: A checkpoint is the moment when the database system ensures that all changes up to that point are written to the actual database files on disk. Checkpoints can be triggered automatically or manually. Postgres Postgres has a dedicated checkpointer background process that is responsible to ensure that the data recorded in WAL is periodically and safely written to the main database files on disk. You can trigger checkpoints manually using the SQL command CHECKPOINT
38.title: Checkpointing

39.body: Multi-Version Concurrency Control Each transaction sees a snapshot of the database at a particular point in time. Example Postgres maintains cocistency and visibility of data through its MVCC system
